{"/service/ndnp/ct/batch_ct_grasso_ver02/data/sn82014085/00393346966/1937120201/0527.xml":{"full_text":"Vatarfari PcKttrafl\nPublished Mr; Evening Except Bundsy*\ntad HoUdey* by\nthe waterbuhv democrat. ma\nOwnocnt Building, Weterbury, Conn.\nj*irw\u2014*-'\u2022\nSubscription Rates. Payable In Advance\nOne Year\nSix Month*\n\u2022BOO\nMAO\nOne Month\nOne Week\n75c\n18C\nMember of Audit Bureau ot Circulation\nThe Democrat will not return manuscript sent\nm for publication unles* accompanied by postage\nNo attention paid anonymous communication*.\nDial 4-3111 .dffVTEtot 4\u2018t121\nAll Department* All Department*\nA Thought for Today\nThere la nothing from without a man, (hat\nentering Into him can defile him; but the things\nwhich come out of him, those are they that de\nfile the man.\u2014Mark 7:15.\n\nSuch as thy words are, such will thy affections\nbe estceemed; and such will thy deeds as thy\naffections, and such thy life as thy deeds.\u2014\nSocrates.\n\nRelief Sense\nThere has been a widespread tendency\nfor voters to turn a deaf ear to local re\nlief requirements. The same citizens\nwho demand that the federal government\nget out of the relief business refuse to per\nmit their local governments to take over\nthe job- They turn down welfare levies\nand lobby against state legislation which\nmight meet conditions respectably.\nThe mayor of one city particularly hard\nhit by such shortsighted action recently\nspoke his mind on the subject. First he\nwarned his fellow-citizens that failure\nto take care of the destitute unemployed\ninvites lawlessness and foments anarchy.\nHe called on every thoughtful citizen\nto help form a general public lobby to\nfight the lobbying of \"selfish and spe\ncial interests\u201d against adequate relief\nlegislation for the state. He even named\na few selfish interests outright.\nPerhaps the thing we need most to\nrealize about relief problems is that ignor\ning them does not save a community\nmoney in the end, because it only permits\na bad condition to become worse. There\nis no justice or wisdom in punishing all\nthe needy unemployed just because there\nare chiselers among them. The com\nmunity that tackles its relief problem\nrealistically will furnish enough money to\ndiscover and weed out the grafters. It\nwill also make employables out of many\nunemployables by sensible health work,\nnnd will put all of them on some decent\nliving regime while their legitimate need\nlasts.\nU. S. Can Avoid War\nThe first and biggest step in the pro\ncess of getting a country ready for a war\nis to sell it on the idea that if war comes\nit can\u2019t possibly stay out. We are get\nting a sizable dose of that sort of sales\ntalk right now. It is raining in on us\nfrom all sides, and the argument runs\nabout like this: If a major war starts\nanywhere, the world is so much a unit\nnowadays that its effects are felt every\nwhere. Isolation is impossible; we got\ntangled up in the last war and we shall\ninevitably get tangled up in the next one.\nSo we might as well make up our minds\nto it, and cooperate wtih other nations\nnow in an effort to keep the war from\nstarting.\nNow it may be true that we could\nprofitably cooperate for the sake of world\npeace\u2014if any major power showed the\nslightest willingness to make any sacri\nfices for peace which to date none of them\nhas done. But it is about time that some\none got up in meeting and pointed out\nthe utter absurdity of saying that we can\u2019t\npossibly stay out of the next war. Of\ncourse we can stay out of it. Nobody is\ngoing to be insane enough to come over\nhere and attack us; if we just make up\nour minds that we aren\u2019t going to do any\nfighting off our home lot, and stick to it,\nthen we stay out of war. It is as simple\nas that.\nOf course, it might be expensive. Whole\nvolumes have been written to show that we\nwould have lost billions of dollars in 1917\nif we had accepted the German submar\nine campaign and remained at peace.\nOur business boom would have collapsed,\nforeign trade would have stagnated, fi\nnancial markets would have gone into a\ntailspin and there would have been the\ndickens to pay generally. But the answer\nto that is simple: we lost billions of dol\nlars anyway, in the long run. and saddled\nourselves with a mess of trouble that\nwe still aren\u2019t entirely out from under.\nFrom a dollars and cents viewpoint it\nwould have been far cheaper if our gov\nernment had bought up all the foreign\norders that were outstanding in 1917\u2014or\nders for guns, shell, steel, cotton, wheat,\noil and all the rest\u2014paid the sellers in\nhard cash, towed the whole lot out to the\nmiddle of the ocean, and sunk it there.\nOur government paid the bills anyway, in\nthe long run. By going to war it simply\ntook on some billions of dollars worth of\nother obligations\u2014and, just incidentally,\nsent about 150,000 young Americans to\ntheir deaths.\nThe expenses of any course of action\nare relative. It is quite true that as the\nworld is now operated it can be fear\nfully expensive for a nation like ours to\nremain at pace when everybody else is\nfighting. But there is this to remember;\nthat nothing possibly can be as ruin\nously expensive as a war. We ought to\nkeep that fact in mind when people start\ntelling us how '\u2018inevitable\u2019\u2019 our participa\ntion in the next war is going to be.\nWorst Public Nuisancos\nDecent people are rapidly getting\n\"led up\u201d on gangsters. This is true even\nof the lunatic and sentimental fringes of\nour society that have regarded them as\nheroes. And no wonder. Such an Inci\ndent as occurred In Detroit on Thanks\ngiving eve Is certainly calculated to alien\nate tne gunmen\u2019s \"public\u201d.\nTwo of these gallant gentry entered a\ncrowded restaurant and, seeing a rival\ngangster standing at the bar with some\nof his own \u201cmob\"\u2019, started shooting, re\n?;ardless of the surrounding throng. The\nellows attacked started shooting back,\nwith the same cheerful disregard of their\nneighbors. The melee ended with one of\nthese human rats killed, two more wound\ned, and two innocent customers one\nof them dining with his wife seriously\nhurt. The executions were all to the good,\nso far as social benefit goes; but the way\nsuch marauders ride over and shoot up\nwhat we call our civilization is a con\ntinuing scandal.\nIt would be wonderful If they could all\nbe herded by themselves into an arena\nwith solid concrete walls, and permitted\nto exterminate themselves in their own\nblithe way. Since that is impractical,\nfor lack or their cooperation, there seems\nto be no effective procedure but for Q\nmen and their local allies in the infested\nregions to eliminate the nuisance by copy\ning their technique but with some\nwhat more regard for bystanders.\nBuy and Use the Seals!\nAn item which ought to be on every\nChristmas list is the Christmas Seal. All\nover the country the annual sale of anti\ntuberculosis seals has already begun. A\npenny for a single stamp or a dollar for a\nsheet of 100 stamps it doesn\u2019t matter\nwhether you can afford only a few or a\ngreat many, just so you buy some.\nOnce bought, the seals should be used.\nTheir purpose is twofold. The money\nraised is used to pay for tuberculosis\ntreatment or preventive work in the local\ncommunity. The stamps themselves,\nstuck on letters and the backs of Christ\nmas packages, perform an educational\nservice, carrying everywhere the good\nword that something can be done and is\nbeing done to stamp out the white plague,\nDecember came in and said hello in a\nsnappy and crisp manner. Frost glist\nened on, well, in lieu of pumpkins,\nhousetops, mail boxes, ash cans and what\nhave you. December comes last in the\nyear\u2019s calendar, but with its outward\ncharacteristics of glum winter, it is first\nin the expression of \u201cpeace on earth.\u2019\u2019\nIt ushers in the advent season, prepara\ntory to one of the most thrilling dramas\nof all time, the birth of Jesus Christ. With\nits coming one makes an effort to enter\ninto the proper spirit of the season, spir\nitually as well as temporally. The\nbusiness recession has cramped the styles\nof many. The outlook hasn\u2019t been too\ngood; and just when we seemed to be\nsailing along for happier days. However,\ncasting aside pessimism, and with a hope\nful optimism we can but hope that every\nthing is for the best in this best of little\nworlds. The thing to do, we are well\nadvised, is not to verve too much to the\nleft or too much to the right, but to keep\nto a sane middle course.\nWaterbury is taking on a Christmas-y\nlook. Garlands have been hung along tho\nmain business thoroughfares. Stores are\ndisplaying holiday goods, and merchants\nurging to shop early. This week the crowds\nin the streets seem much larger; stores\nseem to be busier, and it is to be hoped\nthat shopping will encourage the mer\nchant who has been somewhat cast down\nby the business recession. This week and\nnext Christmas club checks will be\nmailed out, which will mean Increased\nbusiness. The slogan \u201cdo your Christ\nmas shopping early\u201d is a hackneyed one\nbut also a wise one.\nLondon has just experienced one of its\nworst fogs; as pea-soupy, we read, or\ndenser than those described by the es\ntimable Charles Dickens. London has\nalways, at intervals, appreciated heavy\nfogs, and bad as each one is, the^e is al\nways a worse one to come. Just fancy\nstanding on a street corner and not being\nable to see your hand in front of you,\nyour feet under you or the electric light\nat your shoulder.\nEly and Josephine Culbertson come to\nthe marital parting of the ways. They\nwill remain, however, bridge partners.\nW# pass.\nSelected Poem\nSMALL DREAM\n(Prances Frost In the New York Times)\nAnd down the other side of dream\nand up this side of heaven,\nI smelled a hoarse and hilly stream\nand grass that grew uneven.\nAnd up the farther side of hill\nand down Into the hollow,\nI heard the small gray whippoorwill\nflick feather toward his lellow.\nAnd over back the nearest ridge\nI tasted moonlight burning,\nand saw the smoke rise from the edge\nof restless mountains turning.\nAnd lying prone upon the grass\nI touched the dewy thistle,\nand rose and let the midnight pass\nwithout a ghost of whistle.\nDaily Almanac\nSun rises 6:58 a. m.; sets 4:34 p. m.\nAll vehicles must be lighted thirty minutes\nafter sunset.\nNovember was unseasonable, generally\nspeaking. It produced more rain and warm\nweather than Is customary for this prelude\nto winter. Rainfall exceeded that of previous\nyears with temperatures also rising above\nthe mean. Three of the four Saturdays were\nwet. one of Ahem snowy. There was a heat\nwave around 70 degrees and a cold wave\ndown below 30.\nEAST IS WEST\ncn y\nPHILOSOPHICAL,\nKY FRltHfc\nIT is\nWRlTTlM THAT\nPATltNCt\nIS A GREAT\nVIRTUE\nState Aid For Snow\nJustification Seen for Cities, Towns Relying on\nState, Federal Governments for Aid.\nMERIDEN JOURNAL\nCity officials have got the habit\nnow of looking to the state and fed\neral governments to make Improve\nments and perform services for the\ncities that the municipalities always\nused to take care of themselves.\nThere is some Justification for this\nA Book a Day\nStirring Boyhood Adventure\nAgainst Foreign Background\nPeriodically Bruce Catton\u2019s\nBook-a-Day column la turned\nover to Olive Roberts Barton,\nnoted child training authority.\nHere Is her latest review of\nbooks suitable for children.\n\nBY OLIVE ROBERTS BARTON\nIf a boy likes vicarious adventure\nagainst a foreign background, S. 8.\nSmith is his author. A gang of the\nbesprlzornl, or wild boys who\nroamed Russia during the early\nCommune, become secret agents\nfor the OOPU in \u201cThe Spy Mys\ntery\u201d (Harcourt, Brace: $2).\nTheir leader, Grisha, uncovers a\nplot within the government itself.\nThrough his own fine leadership,\nhe lifts his friends out of misery\nand neglect and finds a way to\nsave his country.\nAny high school boy interested\nin modern mechanics will enjoy\n\"Portraits of the Iron Horse,\u201d by\nOtto Kuhler and Robert 8. Henry\n(Rand-McNally: $2). Pictured and\ndescribed in technical detail arc\nAmerican locomotives from the\nearliest to the present streamlined\nmodels.\nFor the 10-to-12-year old who\nwants an unusual story flavored\nwith humor and excitement, there\nis \u201cThe Lost 'Chicken Henry\u2019,\" by\nNed Andrews (Mororw: $2). Chappo\nand Bud, the same young cowboys\nwho made their appearance in tho\nhilarious \"Jerky,\" find themselves\npossessed of a gold mine, called the\n\"Chicken Henry.\" Trouble results.\nChappo tells the story; the author\nunderstood a boy's soul when he\ncreated him.\nA story as entrancing as Us title,\nfor younger girls, Is \"Moonshine\nin Candle Street,\u201d by Constance\nSavery (Longmans: $1.75), where\nin a sprite of a girl who calls her\nself \"Lady Moonshine\" moves into\nthe household of an earnest young\nfan-maker, Mr. Ned.\nHer elfin naughtiness leads\nneighborhood children into one\nscrape after another, until the\nburning of his fan ruins Mr. Ned.\nThen the little lady does an about\nface, and by her personal sacrifice\nbrings the fate of the people on\nCandle Street to a happy denoue\nment. A delightful story, height\nened by Reginald Birch illustra\ntions.\nTwo exquisite new books for\nvery little children are about\nSiamese cats. Clare T. Newbery\nmade her remarkable cat water\ncolors known in \"Mittens.\u201d Now ap\npears \u201cBabette\" (Harpers: $1.50),\nwith a text about a little girl who\nloved the kitten down the hall so\nmuch that she got it for Christmas.\nThe other book Is the true story\nof \"Sakimura\u201d (Viking: $1.50),\nZhenya Gay's own Siamese cat who\nran away from home to find\nfriends. Each page has a full-sized\nlithograph in color of the stately\nSakl.\n(Copyright, 1937, NEA Service, Inc.)\nCurrent Comment\nChina can hold out against Japan\nfor five years if necessary.\n\u2014Generalissimo Chlang Kai-shek.\nWe\u2019ve traced the genealogy to\n1632. and I\u2019m the only one ever to\nbe arrested.\n\u2014William R. Parmele, Toledo,\nJailed on check charges.\n\nLeaders come and go. but the\npeople remain.\n\u2014Josef Stalin. Soviet dictator.\n\nSo prevalent is propaganda that\ndiplomacy has become almost syn\nonymous with deceit.\n\u2014The Rev. Or. R. W. Soclunan.\nNew York city.\nframe of mind because the upper\ngovernmental divisions now take\nheavily from local citizens and they\nreturn some of the taxes when so\ndisposed.\nOfficial New Haven has started\nsomething more In this direction by\nasking the State Highway depart\nment to give a hand In clearing\nsnow off the main arteries passing\nthrough the city. There is some\nground for this move in view of the\naction by the last legislature which\nprovided for state maintenance of\ntwo main thoroughfares in each\ncity. The Joker in the act was that\nno funds were made available by\nwhich to carry out its provisions.\nIt would not be surprising if the\nnext legislature acted in earnest to\nallocato funds paid in by motorists\nto keep certain city streets in a\npassable condition. Motorists would\nprobably not object in view of the\nmiserable Job that most cities make\nin clearing the snow from the main\narteries of travel.\nTowns get service from the state\nsnowplows and maintenance forces\nbut few cities do. Meriden Is one of\nthe exceptions. The state takes all\nthe core of Broad street through\nthis city and makes a particularly\ngood job of snow removal. Else\nwhere In the city, it proceeds only\nto the Inner limits and leaves the\ncentral thoroughfares for the streect\ndepartment to take care of. The lo\ncal budgeteers hold down this ex\npense as much as possible, ever\nhopeful that Providence will be\nkind In the matter of snow, and\nthe clearance money has to come\nfrom other sources.\nThat policy tends to make the\nofficials hesitant about jumping\nInto snow removal as It should be\nundertaken, In some cities, and the\nresult Is clogged streets which are\nharmful to business and not con\nducive to cheer among the citizens.\nThey would undoubtedly welcome\nstate aid if It did not add to their\ntax bills.\nPress Comment\nTHE TROUBLESOME LETTER\n\u201cR\u201d\n(New York Herald-Tribune)\nProfessor Robert J. Menncr, of\nYale, writing in the current issue\nof \u201cAmerican Speech,\u201d presents a\nnovel explanation of why so many\npeople (chiefly in Brooklyn, accord\ning to popular belief) say \"erl\u201d for\n\"oil.\" The professor\u2019s theory\u2014and\nhe seems pretty sure about all this\u2014\nis that people who \"erl\u201d do so be\ncause they are trying very hard, too\nhard, to pronounce the word cor\nrectly. That is to say, they have\nbeen suffering over the knowledge\nthat they say \"bold\u201d for \"bird,\" and\nthis results in a reaction against\nthe oil\" sound. Likewise, the pro\nfessor suggests, Connecticut people\nmay say \"carm\u201d for \"calm\" because\nthey are trying to get over their old\nhabit of saying \u201cfahm\u201d for \u201cfarm,\"\nand overdo the effort.\nThese theories sound plausible\nenough, but we suspect that the de\nsires of such mispronouncers to\ncorrect themselves lie rather deeply\nin the subconscious. We say this for\nthe simple reason that the tradi\ntional Brooklynite does not know\nhe Is saying \u201cbold\u201d or \u201cerl.\u201d He be\nlieves in his heart, and will fight for\nhis belief, that he is really saying\n\"bird\u201d and \"oil.\" He also thinks\nhe is saying \u201claw\u201d and \"jaw\" when\nactually he is saying \u2018lawr\u201d and\n\"Jawr.\" This is true in parts of both\nBrooklyn and Staten Island, a cir\ncumstance which is a perpetual puz\nzle to visitors. We suggest that\nProfessor Menner and his colleagues\npursue this research further. What\nwe particularly want to denow is this\nWhy do so many people from the\nCarolines say \u201cgyarden\u201d for \"gar\nden\"? What are they correcting?\nHOUSEWTVE8 BEST FIREMEN\nCleveland, (UP)\u2014When firemen\nof suburban EucUd reached the\nburning home of I. A. Brandt they\nfound that neighboring housewives\nhad organized their own garden\nhose brigade and had the flames\nunder control.\nAnswers To\nQuestions.\nBy Frederick M. Kerby\nYOUR QUESTIONS ANSWERED\nEnclose a three-cent stamp for\nreply when addressing any ques\ntion of fact or Information to the\nWaterbury Democrat's Service Bu\nreau at Washington. Legal and\nmedical advice cannot be given,\nnor can extended research be un\ndertaken. Be sure all mall Is ad\ndressed to the WATERBURY\nDEMOCRAT'S SERVICE BU\nREAU, 1013 Thirteenth Street,\nWashington, D. C.\nTHE EDITOR.\nQ. When President Lincoln first\ntook office, how many former presi\ndents were living?\nA. Five: Van Buren, Tyler, Fill\nmore, Pierce, and Buchanan.\nQ. How much is the federal sur\ntax on $150,000?\nA. $50,000.\nQ. What is vicuna cloth?\nA. It is made from the wool of\nthe vicuna, a small camelold mam\nTODAY\u2019S COMMON ERROR\nNever pronounce Industry\u2014In\ndus\u2019-trl; say, In\u2019-dus-trl.\nmal of the Andes, or an imitation of\nit made from fine merino wool. The\nvicuna is allied to the dofnestlcatcd\nllama and alpaca.\nQ. How should the name Flrpo\nbe pronounced?\nA. Feer-po.\nQ. Did Dick Grace, famous stunt\nflyer, serve in the United States air\nforces during the World war?\nA. He served in the U. S. naval\nnlr service from September, 1917, to\nMay, 1919, and was with the north\nern bombing group in France and\nwith the naval detachment in Bol\nsena, Italy.\nQ. Are mushrooms classed as a\nvegetable?\nA. Botonically they may be\nclassed as fruit, but on tho market\nthey are listed under vegetables.\nQ. Where are the highest and\nlowest points in the State of Ohio?\nA. The highest is Campbell Hill,\nin Logan county, 1,550 feet above\nsea level; the lowest is the Ohio\nriver in Hamilton county, 425 feet\nabove sea level.\nQ. How many persons are em\nployed on the staffs of prisons and\nreformatories in the United States?\nA. The total number in 1935, in\ncluding wardens, superintendents,\nphysicians, teachers, keepers, cleri\ncal, and miscellaneous employes,\nwas 14,394.\nQ. Do debtors or creditors bene\nfit most by currency inflation?\nA. Debtors and all those who\nhave contracted to pay specified\nsums of money gain at the expense\nof all creditors.\nQ. What is the average cost-per\nmlle on company-owned fleets of\nautomobiles in the lower price class?\nA. The reported average cost\npcr-mile is primarily 3.61 cents.\nQ. What language is spoken in\nIraq?\nA. Arabic.\nQ. When and where was the first\nHassam cement-bound macadam\npavement laid, and when was it\nused first in the United States?\nA. The first one was built at\nEdinburgh, Scotland, in 1872 and is\nstill in service. This method of high\nway construction was uled first in\nthe United States in 1906, in Lynn,\nMass. Modern American practice,\nhowever, dates only from 1932.\nQ. What do the figures on the\nN. R. A. stamp represent?\nA. A farmer, business man, in\ndustrial worker and a woman em\nployee.\nIf yea want a copy ef ear book\nlet \u201cCANDY MAKING,\" write the\nWaterbury Democrat\u2019s Washington\nBores u. 1913 Thirteenth Street,\nWashington, D. C. Enclose M cents\nin postage.\nP\u00abny\nWashington\nVinson Blocks Senate Drive For\nTax Revision This Session;\nFDR Angles fof Fish and Pepper;\nWage-Hour Proselytizing Later\nWASHINGTON, December 2. The trouble with\nthe congressional drive for immediate amputation of the\ncapital gains and undistributed profits taxes is that while\nit has plenty of will, it lacks a way.\nir tne senate couia get at tne\ntwo taxes it would cut them up\nso fast It would make your head\nswim for there Is overwhelming\nsentiment for revision lnstanter, If\nnot for outright repeal. But the\nrub Is that the Seante has no\nImmediate say-so In the matter.\nInitiating tax legislation Is a\nHouse prerogative and that is\nwhere the President has the drop\non the Senate.\nChairman of the Ways and\nMeans subcommittee now for\nmulating the new tax bill Is\nRepresentative Fred M. Vinson.\nBesides being a strong New\nDealer and ardent supporter of\nthe two taxes, the able Ken\ntuckian Is on his way to a life\nJob on the V. S. Court of Ap\npeals In the District of Colum\nbia. His appointment was an\nnounced last week.\nThe federal Judge-to-be sem no\nreason why special favors should\nbe extended to the capital gains\nand undistributed profits taxes. He\nholds with Roosevelt that aptlon\non these two taxes should be\npart of a general overhauling of\nthe tax system, and. further, that\nIt makes no difference whether\nlegislation Is pasesd now or two\nmonths later, since the changes\nwill not apply to this year's re\nturns anyway.\nAlso like the President, Vinson\nIs convinced that the hurry-up\ndrive on the two taxes Is a smoke\nscreen to jam through a sales\ntax.\nIn his key post as committee\nchairman, Vinson Is in a stra\ntegic position to make his\nopinions stick\u2014particularly be\ncause he is the only member of\nthe committee who really knows\nwhat the tax fight is all about.\n(He is one of the few tax ex\nperts In Congress.)\nIf Vinson were for Immediate\naction there would be tas: legis\nlation by Christmas. But he Isn't\nand that is where the President\nhas the laugh on the boys In the\nSenate. They can orate and ful\nminate all they want, but except\nfor making a lot of noise, they\ncan't do a thing.\nThe next move Is up to Judge\nelect Vinson and he will not make\nIt until some time In January.\nHull Illumination\nMichael J. McDermott, press\nliaison officer of the State De\npartment, brought his young son,\nMickey, age four, to the Depart\nment building on a recent holiday.\n\u201cDaddy,\u201d asked Mickey, \u201cIs\nSecretary Hull here?\u201d\n\u201cNo, not now, Sonny,\" said\nMcDermott.\nWhen they reached the fourth\nfloor, Miekey remarked that the\nhall was very dark. \u201cWhy Is It\nso dark, Daddy?\u201d he asked.\n\u201cI guess somebody blew a\nfuse.\u201d\n\u201cOh, then that's why Mr.\nHull Isn\u2019t here. He's gone out\nto buy a new fuse.\u201d\nPolitical Fishing\nThe warm swells of the Oulf\nStream are not the only waters\nIn which the President will fish\nduring his Florida Junket. In\nfact, his piscatorial Junket Is part\nly a screen for more serious angl\ning.\nPrivately, Roosevelt la anxious to\nsee Florida\u2019s rookie Senator Claude\nPepper renominated next spring,\nand Alabama's seven-term Repre\nsentative Lister Hill win the Janu\nary primary for Justice Black's\nseat. Young, able New Dealers,\nRoosevelt considers them the\nprogressive type which the Demo\ncratic party needs In the South.\nBut eager as he Is to help\nthem, It' would be Impolitic to do\nso openly. Pepper\u2019s announced\nopponent, Representative Mark\nWlleox, and Hill\u2019s rival, \"Tom\ntom\" Heflin, also profess to be\nNew Dealers\u2014 with reservations.\nHowever, there Is more than one\nway to skin a oat.\nOutwardly, Roosevelt will do no\npoliticking for Pepper or Hill.\nBut he will execute what Is known\nIn cloakroom parlance as the very\npotent rite of \"laying on of\nhands\u201d In a way voters won\u2019t miss.\nPepper and Hill will be seen\nprominently In his company, have\ntheir pictures taken with him and\nwill be affectionately referred to\nas \"Claude and Lister\u201d.\nWilcox and Heflin have not\nbeen Invited to be around. The\nInference is obvious.\nWage-Hour Fishing\nThe President has still another\nunannounced mission on his\nSouthern trip.\nOn return, he plans to do some\nquiet proselyting for the Wage\nHour bill among the eight gov\nernors of the Southeastern Gov\nernors Conference during his stop\nover in Gainesville, Qa., where he\nwill dedicate a park.\nUndercover, the Conference\nhas been sharpshooting at the\nWage-Hour measure, and Roose\nvelt will try to persuade the\ngovernors to lay off. As they\nhave favors to ask of him, he\nmay be able to make a trade.\nNOTE: Definitely not slated for\nbenediction is Georgia\u2019s rabidly\nanti-New Deal Senator Walter\nGeorge, who also comes up for re\nelection next year.\nSol\u2019s Founding Fathers\nTo see Sol Bloom show off the\nrare exhibit of portraits of the\nFounding Fathers now on display\nIn Washington\u2019s Corcoran Art\nGallery, one might think he was\ntheir grandfather.\nThe owners of the pictures, SOI\nexplains, were very generous. In\nassembling the collection, he en\ncountered trouble only with gov\nernment officials.\n\u201cWest Point,\u2019* Sol complained,\n\"has a fine portrait of Jefferson,\nbut they wouldn\u2019t let us have It.\nI appealed to the secretary of\nwar, but it did no good.\n\u201cThen Senator Lodge has\nsome nlpe things, but he\nwouldn\u2019t lend them to us.\nNolther would Senator Gerry.\u201d\nThe man who gave Sol the\ngreatest pain, however, was Mayor\nWilson of Philadelphia, who re\nfused to lend some of the por\ntraits from Independence Hall.\n\u201cOther Philadelphians,\u201d said\nSol, \u201cwho are descendants of\nthe signers, let us have their\npictures. But not Wilson. What\nwas it to him? He hasn\u2019t any\nancestors.\u201d\nNOTE: The pictures exhibited\nhere are specially Insured for\nthree million dollars. They were\nbrought to Washington by van,\nwith an extra van ahead and\nanother behind, for protection.\nMerry-Go-Round\nAsked why, if he favored pas\nsage of the Wage-Hour bill, ha\ndidn\u2019t sign the discharge petition\nthat would bring it to the House\nfloor for a vote, Chairman John\nO\u2019Connor of the Rules Commit\ntee replied, \u201cI can recognize\ndemogoguery when I see it. In\nfact, I Indulge in it myself at\ntimes, but I never vote to fire\nmyself\".Labor's Non-par\ntisan League has quietly begun or\nganizing state campaign commit\ntees in preparation for the 1838\nprimaries Latest publica\ntion to make its appearance on\ncongressional desks Is News-Let\nter Magazine, devoted to social\nsecurity legislation of all kinds.\n(Copyright, 1937, by United\nFeature Syndicate, Inc.)\nTest Your\nKnowledge\nCan yon answer seven of\nthese test questions? Turn to\nlast paqe for the answers.\n1. What Is the tympanic mem\nbrane of the human ear commonly\ncalled?\n2. Name the prospective bride of\nPrince Paul, heir apparent to the\nthrone of Oreece.\nS. What do the initials NIRB\nstand for?\n4. At a dinner dance, should a\nman ash his hostess or his dinner\npartner for the first dance?\n8. How many grains are In an\nounce of pure gold?\n8. In which state are the Finger\nLakes?\n7. What Is the name of the Philip\nMorris page boy?\n8. In Freudian psychology, what Is\nan oedlpus complex?\n9. Who signs the acts that are\npassed over the veto of the Pres\nident?\n10. Name the Generalissimo and\nhead of the Chinese government.\nOFF THE RECORD\nBy Ed Reed\n\n\u25a0ppspapipi!\n\nteller I\nBANK\n*oiun\u00a3\nI\n/X~r\n\"I\u2019d like to deposit this here until after Xmas\u2014there are too\nbank examiners at home!\u201d","height":"28468","width":"21144"}}
